1950s post-war Europe setting (maybe even earlier, like 1920s post WWI). Teachers, staff, and students are all war orphans. Adults have lost their families (for the most part), some fought as conscripted soldiers, the students have no identifiable family. They're in an informal institution that once was a private estate, later converted to a private academy. Some buildings are 200-300 years old, 30-40 acres of land, isolated, a couple dozen buildings at most, half are dormitories & cottages for teachers. Two or three small towns "sort of" nearby, populations about 10K-12K each; "big city" of ~300K population is a half day train ride from one of the small towns. Mixed architecture from Romanian/Frankenstein to Industrial Revolution stark ironworks. Large library with archaic & rare books, not entirely organized & in order. A pair of nearly abandoned science buildings, old equipment, mostly abandoned 20-30 years ago, used for medical & biological labs and research/teaching.

Add onto the post-world war aftermath society, also a worldwide plague is in its final throes (consider it similar to the Spanish Flu of 1918/1919). In this time frame, the world feels like it's post-Apocalypse from the perspective of the survivors.

After first few months, a small government inspection team arrives. Underfunded, overworked, trying to get a perfunctory evaluation on paper, get out & onto bigger more important projects. Protagonist establishes some contact with them, but it's by phone & handwritten letters. Does get some feedback from some individuals, eventually establishes contact with government agency in the capitol.

New students arrive from various places, all with no or very little family. Common theme seems there is money to cover their costs, even if not luxuriously. Seems different villages & towns are sending them here due to lack of family at their origin. Some minor language & cultural issues, added to girl & PTSD issues.

Working title: The Forgotten Place
